# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: odin-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] In computing, **data-oriented design** is a program optimization approach motivated by efficient usage of the CPU cache, often used in video game development.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] The approach is to focus on the data layout, separating and sorting fields according to when they are needed, and to think about transformations of data.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] Proponents include Mike Acton, Scott Meyers, and Jonathan Blow.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] The parallel array (or structure of arrays) is the main example of data-oriented design.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] It is contrasted with the *array of structures* typical of object-oriented designs.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] The definition of data-oriented design as a programming paradigm can be seen as contentious as many believe that it can be used side by side with another paradigm, but due to the emphasis on data layout, it is also incompatible with most other paradigms.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] These methods became especially popular in the mid to late 2000s during the seventh generation of video game consoles that included the IBM PowerPC based PlayStation 3 (PS3) and Xbox 360 consoles.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] Historically, game consoles often have relatively weak central processing units (CPUs) compared to the top-of-line desktop computer counterparts.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] This is a design choice to devote more power and transistor budget to the graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] For example, the 7th generation CPUs were not manufactured with modern out-of-order execution processors, but instead use in-order processors with high clock speeds and deep pipelines.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] In addition, most types of computing systems have main memory located hundreds of clock cycles away from the processing elements.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] Furthermore, as CPUs have become faster alongside a large increase in main memory capacity, there is massive data consumption that increases the likelihood of cache misses in the shared bus, otherwise known as Von Neumann bottlenecking.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] Consequently, locality of reference methods have been used to control performance, requiring improvement of memory access patterns to fix bottlenecking.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] Some of the software issues were also similar to those encountered on the Itanium, requiring loop unrolling for upfront scheduling.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] The claim is that traditional object-oriented programming (OOP) design principles result in poor data locality, more so if runtime polymorphism (dynamic dispatch) is used (which is especially problematic on some processors).
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] Although OOP appears to "organise code around data", it actually organises source code around data types rather than physically grouping individual fields and arrays in an efficient format for access by specific functions.
[src:odin-lang/data-oriented-design] Moreover, it often hides layout details under abstraction layers, while a data-oriented programmer wants to consider this first and foremost.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] In computer science, **manual memory management** refers to the usage of manual instructions by the programmer to identify and deallocate unused objects, or garbage.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Up until the mid-1990s, the majority of programming languages used in industry supported manual memory management, though garbage collection has existed since 1959, when it was introduced with Lisp.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Today, however, languages with garbage collection such as Java are increasingly popular and the languages Objective-C and Swift provide similar functionality through Automatic Reference Counting.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] The main manually managed languages still in widespread use today are C and C++ – see C dynamic memory allocation.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Many programming languages use manual techniques to determine when to *allocate* a new object from the free store.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] C uses the `malloc` function; C++ and Java use the `new` operator; and many other languages (such as Python) allocate all objects from the free store.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Determining when an object ought to be created (object creation) is generally trivial and unproblematic, though techniques such as object pools mean an object may be created before immediate use.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] The real challenge is object destruction – determination of when an object is no longer needed (i.e. is garbage), and arranging for its underlying storage to be returned to the free store for re-use.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Manual memory management is known to enable several major classes of bugs into a program when used incorrectly, notably violations of memory safety or memory leaks.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] These are a significant source of security bugs.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Languages which exclusively use garbage collection are known to avoid the last two classes of defects.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Memory leaks can still occur (and bounded leaks frequently occur with generational or conservative garbage collection), but are generally less severe than memory leaks in manual systems.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Manual memory management has one correctness advantage, which is that it allows automatic resource management via the resource acquisition is initialization (RAII) paradigm.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] This arises when objects own scarce system resources (like graphics resources, file handles, or database connections) which must be relinquished when an object is destroyed – when the lifetime of the resource ownership should be tied to the lifetime of the object.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Languages with manual management can arrange this by acquiring the resource during object initialization (in the constructor), and releasing during object destruction (in the destructor), which occurs at a precise time.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] This is known as Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII).
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] This can also be used with deterministic reference counting.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] In C++, this ability is put to further use to automate memory deallocation within an otherwise-manual framework, use of smart pointers in the language's standard library to perform memory management is a common paradigm.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] In languages like Rust which enforce strict ownership, RAII becomes the default behavior for managing resources.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] This approach is not usable in most garbage collected languages – notably tracing garbage collectors or more advanced reference counting – due to finalization being non-deterministic, and sometimes not occurring at all.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] That is, it is difficult to define (or determine) when or if a finalizer method might be called; this is commonly known as the finalizer problem.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Programmers are expected to invoke `dispose()` manually as appropriate to prevent "leaking" of scarce graphics resources.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] A defer mechanism is a feature that allows the postponing of execution of a piece of code until later, usually either the end of scope or end of a function.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] This can be seen as similar to a finally block in other languages.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] C (beginning in C29) introduces a `defer` mechanism.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Each `defer` block which is encountered in execution is run at scope exit (not when encountered), in the reverse order they were encountered.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] C++ has not yet commented on whether or not it will integrate C `defer`, as RAII covers this use case.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] In Go, `defer` is used to schedule a function call to run when the surrounding function returns.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Multiple `defer`s run in last-in-first-out (LIFO) order.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] In Zig, `defer` is block-level and runs when the current scope ends, not just the function.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Unlike Go, Zig `defer` incurs no overhead.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Zig also includes `errdefer`, which runs only if the function exits with an error.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Many advocates of manual memory management argue that it affords superior performance when compared to automatic techniques such as garbage collection.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Traditionally latency was the biggest advantage, but this is no longer the case.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Manual allocation frequently has superior locality of reference.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Manual allocation is also known to be more appropriate for systems where memory is a scarce resource, due to faster reclamation.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Latency is a debated point that has changed over time, with early garbage collectors and simple implementations performing very poorly compared to manual memory management, but sophisticated modern garbage collectors often performing as well or better than manual memory management.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] Manual allocation does not suffer from the long "pause" times that occur in simple stop-the-world garbage collection, although modern garbage collectors have collection cycles which are often not noticeable.
[src:odin-lang/manual-memory-management] This is especially an issue in real time systems, where unbounded collection cycles are generally unacceptable; real-time garbage collection is possible by pausing the garbage collector, while real-time manual memory management requires avoiding large deallocations, or manually pausing deallocation.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Odin is a general-purpose programming language with distinct typing built for high performance, modern systems and data-oriented programming.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Odin is the C alternative for the Joy of Programming.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Odin has been designed for readability, scalability, and orthogonality of concepts.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Simplicity is complicated to get right, clear is better than clever.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Odin allows for the highest performance through low-level control over the memory layout, memory management and custom allocators and so much more.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Odin is designed from the bottom up for the modern computer, with built-in support for SOA data types, array programming, and other features.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] We go into programming because we love to solve problems.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Why shouldn't our tools bring us joy whilst doing it?
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] JangaFX are the creators of the 3D animation software EmberGen, GeoGen, and LiquiGen, which are *all* written *fully* in Odin.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] EmberGen is a real-time volumetric fluid simulator that can instantly simulate, render, and export flipbooks, image sequences, and VDB volumes.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] With EmberGen, you can create anything from fire and smoke, to explosions and magic wisps.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] EmberGen gives you the creative freedom to iterate on your simulations in a few milliseconds instead of hours.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] LiquiGen is a real-time volumetric liquid simulator that can instantly simulate, render, and export flipbooks, image sequences, and VDB volumes.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] GeoGen is a real-time terrain generation tool.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Through EmberGen, Odin runs in production among the giants of the games and film industries: Bethesda, CAPCOM, Codemasters, THQNordic, Warner Bros, Weta Digital, and many others.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] All product names, logos, and brands are property of their respective owners.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] ChiAha™ Digital Twin Toolkit is written in Odin, and can help answer your factory flow questions.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] ChiAha™ can predict production line performance and OEE within 1% accuracy.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] High-fidelity modeling constructs with statistically modeled data-driven behavior.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] What is the effect on OEE of close-coupling?What speeds should each machine run?How can production be increased?How much will OEE improve with changes to the system?
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Odin comes with high quality packages out of the box in its `core` library.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Odin provides official libraries for all major graphics APIs: OpenGL, Vulkan, Direct3D11, Direct3D12, Metal, wgpu, and WebGL 1 & 2.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Odin additionally brings you officially maintained bindings for popular libraries such as SDL2, GLFW, raylib, microui, miniaudio and much more, in its `vendor` library!
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Odin is an open source programming language and contributions from the community are welcome!
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] If you want to help out, check the issue tracker for open issues that may interest you.
[src:odin-lang/odin-lang-org] Those labelled help wanted are in particular need of community assistance right now.
[src:odin-lang/page] How to download and install the Odin compiler.
[src:odin-lang/page] Both from source or from a binary release, along with a list of per-platform requirements.
[src:odin-lang/page] An overview of the Odin programming language and its features.
[src:odin-lang/page] Documentation for all the official packages part of the `core` and `vendor` library collections.
[src:odin-lang/page] The original demonstration of the Odin in a single file, including numerous examples of concepts and features of the programming language.
[src:odin-lang/page] Answers to commonly asked questions about Odin.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] Systems programming requires a great degree of hardware awareness.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] Its goal is to achieve efficient use of available resources, either because the software itself is performance-critical or because even small efficiency improvements directly transform into significant savings of time or money.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] In systems programming, often limited programming facilities are available.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] The use of automatic garbage collection is not common and debugging is sometimes hard to do.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] The runtime library, if available at all, is usually far less powerful, and does less error checking.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] Because of those limitations, monitoring and logging are often used; operating systems may have extremely elaborate logging subsystems.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] Implementing certain parts in operating systems and networking requires systems programming, for example implementing paging (virtual memory) or a device driver for an operating system.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] Originally systems programmers invariably wrote in assembly language.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] Experiments with hardware support in high level languages in the late 1960s led to such languages as PL/S, BLISS, BCPL, and extended ALGOL for Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] Forth also has applications as a systems language.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] In the 1970s, C became widespread, aided by the growth of Unix.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] More recently a subset of C++ called Embedded C++ has seen some use, for instance it is used in the I/O Kit drivers of macOS.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] Engineers working at Google created Go in 2007 to address developer productivity in large distributed systems, with developer-focused features such as Concurrency, Garbage Collection, and faster program compilation than C and C++.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] In 2015 Rust came out, a general-purpose programming language often used in systems programming.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] Rust was designed with memory safety in mind and to be as performant as C and C++.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] For historical reasons, some organizations use the term *systems programmer* to describe a job function which would be more accurately termed systems administrator.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] This is particularly true in organizations whose computer resources have historically been dominated by mainframes, although the term is even used to describe job functions which do not involve mainframes.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] This usage arose because administration of IBM mainframes often involved the writing of custom assembler code (IBM's Basic Assembly Language (BAL)), which integrated with the operating system such as OS/MVS, DOS/VSE or VM/CMS.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] Indeed, some IBM software products had substantial code contributions from customer programming staff.
[src:odin-lang/systems-programming] This type of programming is progressively less common, and increasingly done in C rather than Assembly, but the term *systems programmer* is still used as the de-facto job title for staff administering IBM mainframes even in cases where they do not regularly engage in systems programming activities.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Development of commercial video games is normally funded by a publisher and can take two to five years to reach completion.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Game creation by small, self-funded teams is called independent development.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The technology in a game may be written from scratch or use proprietary software specific to one company.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] As development has become more complex, it has become common for companies and independent developers alike to use off-the-shelf "engines" such as Unity, Unreal Engine or Godot.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Commercial game development began in the 1970s with the advent of arcade video games, first-generation video game consoles like the Atari 2600, and home computers like the Apple II.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Into the 1980s, a lone programmer could develop a full and complete game such as *Pitfall!*.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] By the second and third generation of video game consoles in the late 1980s, the growing popularity of 3D graphics on personal computers meant higher expectations for visuals and quality, making it difficult for a single person to produce a mainstream video game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The average cost of producing a high-end (often called AAA) game slowly rose from US$1–4 million in 2000, to over $200 million and up by 2023.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] At the same time, independent game development has flourished.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The best-selling video game of all time, *Minecraft*, was initially written by one person before it gained traction.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Mojang was founded to develop it, and it was eventually acquired by Microsoft and greatly expanded.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Mainstream commercial video games are generally developed in phases.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A concept is developed which then moves to pre-production where prototypes are written and the plan for the entire game is created.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] This is followed by full-scale development or *production*, then sometimes a post-production period where the game is polished.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] It has become common for many developers, especially smaller developers, to publicly release games in an "early access" form, where iterative development takes place in tandem with feedback from actual players.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Games are produced through the software development process.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] They are created both as a form of artistic expression and a commercial product intended to generate profit.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Game development is often described as a blend of art and science, reflecting the technical precision and creative design required.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Development is normally funded by a publisher, and careful budget estimation is critical to success.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Poor planning may cause projects to exceed budgets or fail to meet expectations.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In fact, the majority of commercial games do not produce profit.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Most developers therefore plan their production schedule carefully to balance creative goals with available resources.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The game industry requires innovations, as publishers cannot profit from the constant release of repetitive sequels and imitations.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Every year new independent development companies open and some manage to develop hit titles.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Similarly, many developers close down because they cannot find a publishing contract or their production is not profitable.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] It is difficult to start a new company due to the high initial investment required.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Nevertheless, the growth of the casual and mobile game market has allowed developers with smaller teams to enter the market.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Once the companies become financially stable, they may expand to develop larger games.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Most developers start small and gradually expand their business.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A developer receiving profit from a successful title may store up capital to expand and re-factor their company, as well as tolerate more failed deadlines.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] An average development budget for a multiplatform game is US$18-28M, with high-profile games often exceeding $40M.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In the early era of home computers and video game consoles in the early 1980s, a single programmer could handle almost all the tasks of developing a game — programming, graphical design, sound effects, etc.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] It could take as little as six weeks to develop a game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] However, the high user expectations and requirements of modern commercial games far exceed the capabilities of a single developer and require the splitting of responsibilities.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A team of over a hundred people can be employed full-time for a single project.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Game development, production, or design is a process that starts from an idea or concept.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Often the idea is based on a modification of an existing game concept.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The game idea may fall within one or several genres.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Designers often experiment with different combinations of genres.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A game designer generally writes an initial game proposal document, that describes the basic concept, gameplay, feature list, setting and story, target audience, requirements and schedule, and finally staff and budget estimates.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Different companies have different formal procedures and philosophies regarding game design and development.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] There is no standardized development method; however commonalities exist.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A game developer may range from a single individual to a large multinational company.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] There are both independent and publisher-owned studios.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Independent developers rely on financial support from a game publisher.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] They usually have to develop a game from concept to prototype without external funding.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The formal game proposal is then submitted to publishers, who may finance the game development from several months to years.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The publisher would retain exclusive rights to distribute and market the game and would often own the intellectual property rights for the game franchise.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The publisher may also own the development studio, or it may have internal development studio(s).
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Generally the publisher is the one who owns the game's intellectual property rights.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Many larger development companies work on several titles at once.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] This is necessary because of the time taken between shipping a game and receiving royalty payments, which may be between 6 and 18 months.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Small companies may structure contracts, ask for advances on royalties, use shareware distribution, employ part-time workers and use other methods to meet payroll demands.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Console manufacturers, such as Microsoft, Nintendo, or Sony, have a standard set of technical requirements that a game must conform to in order to be approved.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Additionally, the game concept must be approved by the manufacturer, who may refuse to approve certain titles.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Most modern PC or console games take from three to five years to complete, whereas a mobile game can be developed in a few months.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The length of development is influenced by a number of factors, such as genre, scale, development platform and number of assets.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Some games can take much longer than the average time frame to complete.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] An infamous example is 3D Realms' *Duke Nukem Forever*, announced to be in production in April 1997 and released fourteen years later in June 2011.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Planning for Maxis' game *Spore* began in late 1999; the game was released nine years later in September 2008.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The game *Prey* was briefly profiled in a 1997 issue of PC Gamer, but was not released until 2006, and only then in highly altered form.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Finally, *Team Fortress 2* was in development from 1998 until its 2007 release, and emerged from a convoluted development process involving "probably three or four different games", according to Gabe Newell.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The game revenue from retail is divided among the parties along the distribution chain, such as — developer, publisher, retail, manufacturer and console royalty.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Many developers fail to profit from this and go bankrupt.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Many seek alternative economic models through Internet marketing and distribution channels to improve returns, as through a mobile distribution channel the share of a developer can be up to 70% of the total revenue and through an online distribution channel owned by the developer almost 100%.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The history of game making begins with the development of the first video games, although which video game is the first depends on the definition of *video game*.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The first games created had little entertainment value, and their development focus was separate from user experience—in fact, these games required mainframe computers to play them.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Douglas in 1952, was the first computer game to use a digital display.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 1958, a game called *Tennis for Two*, which displayed its output on an oscilloscope, was made by Willy Higinbotham, a physicist working at the Brookhaven National Laboratory.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 1961, a mainframe computer game called *Spacewar!* was developed by a group of Massachusetts Institute of Technology students led by Steve Russell.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] True commercial design and development of games began in the 1970s, when arcade video games and first-generation consoles were marketed.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 1971, *Computer Space* was the first commercially sold, coin-operated video game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] It used a black-and-white television for its display, and the computer system was made of 74 series TTL chips.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 1972, the first home console system was released called Magnavox Odyssey, developed by Ralph H.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] That same year, Atari released *Pong*, an arcade game that increased video game popularity.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The commercial success of *Pong* led other companies to develop *Pong* clones, spawning the video game industry.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Programmers worked within the big companies to produce games for these devices.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The industry did not see huge innovation in game design and a large number of consoles had very similar games.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Many of these early games were often *Pong* clones.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Some games were different, however, such as *Gun Fight*, which was significant for several reasons: an early 1975 on-foot, multi-directional shooter, which depicted game characters, game violence, and human-to-human combat.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Tomohiro Nishikado's original version was based on discrete logic, which Dave Nutting adapted using the Intel 8080, making it the first video game to use a microprocessor.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Console manufacturers soon started to produce consoles that were able to play independently developed games, and ran on microprocessors, marking the beginning of second-generation consoles, beginning with the release of the Fairchild Channel F in 1976.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The flood of *Pong* clones led to the video game crash of 1977, which eventually came to an end with the mainstream success of Taito's 1978 arcade shooter game *Space Invaders*, marking the beginning of the golden age of arcade video games and inspiring dozens of manufacturers to enter the market.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Its creator Nishikado not only designed and programmed the game, but also did the artwork, engineered the arcade hardware, and put together a microcomputer from scratch.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] It was soon ported to the Atari 2600, becoming the first "killer app" and quadrupling the console's sales.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] At the same time, home computers appeared on the market, allowing individual programmers and hobbyists to develop games.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] This allowed hardware manufacturer and software manufacturers to act separately.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A very large number of games could be produced by an individual, as games were easy to make because graphical and memory limitation did not allow for much content.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Larger companies developed, who focused selected teams to work on a title.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The developers of many early home video games, such as *Zork*, *Baseball*, *Air Warrior*, and *Adventure*, later transitioned their work as products of the early video game industry.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The industry expanded significantly at the time, with the arcade video game sector alone (representing the largest share of the gaming industry) generating higher revenues than both pop music and Hollywood films combined.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The home video game industry, however, suffered major losses following the video game crash of 1983.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Chris Crawford and Don Daglow in 1987 similarly advised prospective designers to write games as a hobby first, and to not quit their existing jobs early.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The home video game industry was revitalized soon after by the widespread success of the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 2000 a 12 to 36 month development project was funded by a publisher for US$1M–3M.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Additionally, $250k–1.5M were spent on marketing and sales development.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 2001, over 3000 games were released for PC; and from about 100 games turning profit only about 50 made significant profit.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In the early 2000s it became increasingly common to use middleware game engines, such as *Quake* engine or Unreal Engine.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In the early 2000s, also mobile games started to gain popularity.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] However, mobile games distributed by mobile operators remained a marginal form of gaming until the Apple App Store was launched in 2008.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 2005, a mainstream console video game cost from US$3M to $6M to develop.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Some games cost as much as $20M to develop.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 2006 the profit from a console game sold at retail was divided among parties of distribution chain as follows: developer (13%), publisher (32%), retail (32%), manufacturer (5%), console royalty (18%).
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 2008 a developer would retain around 17% of retail price and around 85% if sold online.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Since the third generation of consoles, the home video game industry has constantly increased and expanded.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The industry revenue has increased at least five-fold since the 1990s.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 2007, the software portion of video game revenue was $9.5 billion, exceeding that of the movie industry.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The Apple App Store, introduced in 2008, was the first mobile application store operated directly by the mobile-platform holder.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] It significantly changed the consumer behaviour more favourable for downloading mobile content and quickly broadened the markets of mobile games.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 2009 games' market annual value was estimated between $7–30 billion, depending on which sales figures are included.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] This is on par with films' box office market.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A publisher would typically fund an independent developer for $500k–$5M for a development of a title.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 2012, the total value had already reached $66.3 billion and by then the video game markets were no longer dominated by console games.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] According to Newzoo, the share of MMO's was 19.8%, PC/MAC's 9.8%, tablets' 3.2%, smartphones 10.6%, handhelds' 9.8%, consoles' only 36.7% and online casual games 10.2%.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The fastest growing market segments being mobile games with an average annual rate of 19% for smartphones and 48% for tablets.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In the past several years, many developers opened and many closed down.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Each year a number of developers are acquired by larger companies or merge with existing companies.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] For example, in 2007 Blizzard Entertainment's parent company, Vivendi Games merged with Activision.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 2008 Electronic Arts nearly acquired Take-Two Interactive.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In 2009 Midway Games was acquired by Time-Warner and Eidos Interactive merged with Square Enix.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Consolidation of the video game industry has been high on the agenda, especially in the 2020s with acquisition of Bethesda (Zenimax Media) for $7.5bn in 2020 and Activision Blizzard for $69bn in 2023 by Microsoft (Xbox), along with Sony (PlayStation) acquiring Bungie for $3.6bn in 2022.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Development is overseen by internal and external producers.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The producer working for the developer is known as the *internal producer* and manages the development team, schedules, reports progress, hires and assigns staff, and so on.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The producer working for the publisher is known as the *external producer* and oversees developer progress and budget.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Producer's responsibilities include PR, contract negotiation, liaising between the staff and stakeholders, schedule and budget maintenance, quality assurance, beta test management, and localization.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] This role may also be referred to as *project manager*, *project lead*, or *director*.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A video game publisher is a company that publishes video games that they have either developed internally or have had developed by an external video game developer.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] As with book publishers or publishers of DVD movies, video game publishers are responsible for their product's manufacturing and marketing, including market research and all aspects of advertising.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] They usually finance the development, sometimes by paying a video game developer (the publisher calls this external development) and sometimes by paying an internal staff of developers called a studio.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Consequently, they also typically own the IP of the game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Large video game publishers also distribute the games they publish, while some smaller publishers instead hire distribution companies (or larger video game publishers) to distribute the games they publish.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Other functions usually performed by the publisher include deciding on and paying for any license that the game may utilize; paying for localization; layout, printing, and possibly the writing of the user manual; and the creation of graphic design elements such as the box design.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Large publishers may also attempt to boost efficiency across all internal and external development teams by providing services such as sound design and code packages for commonly needed functionality.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Because the publisher usually finances development, it usually tries to manage development risk with a staff of producers or project managers to monitor the progress of the developer, critique ongoing development, and assist as necessary.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Most video games created by an external video game developer are paid for with periodic advances on royalties.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] These advances are paid when the developer reaches certain stages of development, called milestones.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] By definition independent video game developers often shortened to indie devs, create games without funding from a publisher and may choose to digitally distribute their games.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Publishers have indeed provided much needed support for independent developers through various other means including making distribution platforms available.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Developers can range in size from small groups making casual games to housing hundreds of employees and producing several large titles.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Companies divide their subtasks of game development.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Individual job titles may vary; however, roles are the same within the industry.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The development team consists of several members.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Some members of the team may handle more than one role; similarly, more than one task may be handled by the same member.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Team size can vary from 3 to 100 or more members, depending on the game's scope.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The most represented are artists, followed by programmers, then designers, and finally, audio specialists, with one to three producers in management.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Many teams also include a dedicated writer with expertise in video game writing.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Other positions, such as testers, may be employed only part-time.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Use of contractors for art, programming, and writing is standard within the industry.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Salaries for these positions vary depending on both the experience and the location of the employee.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A game designer is a person who designs gameplay, conceiving and designing the rules and structure of a game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Development teams usually have a lead designer who coordinates the work of other designers.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] They are the main visionaries of the game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] One of the roles of a designer is being a writer, often employed part-time to conceive the game's narrative, dialogue, commentary, cutscene narrative, journals, video game packaging content, hint system, etc.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] In larger projects, there are often separate designers for various parts of the game, such as, game mechanics, user interface, characters, dialogue, graphics, etc.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A game artist is a visual artist who creates video game art.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The art production is usually overseen by an *art director* or *art lead*, making sure their vision is followed.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The art director manages the art team, scheduling and coordinating within the development team.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The artist's job may be 2D oriented or 3D oriented.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] *2D artists* may produce concept art, sprites, textures, environmental backdrops or terrain images, and user interface.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] *3D artists* may produce models or meshes, animation, 3D environment, and cinematics.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A game programmer is a software engineer who primarily develops video games or related software (such as game development tools).
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The game's codebase development is handled by programmers.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] There are usually one to several lead programmers, who implement the game's starting codebase and overview future development and programmer allocation on individual modules.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] An entry-level programmer can make, on average, around $70,000 annually and an experienced programmer can make, on average, around $125,000 annually.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A level designer is a person who creates levels, challenges or missions for video games using a specific set of programs.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] These programs may be commonly available commercial 3D or 2D design programs, or specially designed and tailored level editors made for a specific game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Level designers work with both incomplete and complete versions of the game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Game programmers usually produce level editors and design tools for the designers to use.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] This eliminates the need for designers to access or modify game code.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Level editors may involve custom high-level scripting languages for interactive environments or AIs.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] As opposed to the level editing tools sometimes available to the community, level designers often work with placeholders and prototypes aiming for consistency and clear layout before the required artwork is completed.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Sound engineers are technical professionals responsible for sound effects and sound positioning.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] They are sometimes involved in creating haptic feedback, as was the case with the Returnal game sound team at PlayStation Studios Creative Arts in London.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] They sometimes oversee voice acting and other sound asset creation.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Composers who create a game's musical score also comprise a game's sound team, though often this work is outsourced.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The quality assurance is carried out by game testers.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] A game tester analyzes video games to document software defects as part of a quality control.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Testing is a highly technical field requiring computing expertise and analytic competence.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] The testers ensure that the game falls within the proposed design: it both works and is entertaining.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] This involves testing of all features, compatibility, localization, etc.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Although necessary throughout the whole development process, testing is expensive and is often actively utilized only towards the completion of the project.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] During development, testing controller performance is essential.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p01] Using a gamepad tester helps developers detect input lag, button issues, and calibration problems, improving overall game quality.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Game development is a software development process, as a video game is software with art, audio, and gameplay.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Formal software development methods are often overlooked.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Games with poor development methodology are likely to run over budget and time estimates, as well as contain a large number of bugs.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Planning is important for individual and group projects alike.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Overall game development is not suited for typical software life cycle methods, such as the waterfall model.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] One method employed for game development is agile development.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] It is based on iterative prototyping, a subset of software prototyping.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Agile development depends on feedback and refinement of the game's iterations with a gradually increasing feature set.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] This method is effective because most projects do not start with a clear requirement outline.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A popular method of agile software development is Scrum.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Another successful method is Personal Software Process (PSP) requiring additional staff training to increase awareness of project planning.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] This method is more expensive and requires commitment of team members.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] PSP can be extended to Team Software Process, where the whole team is self-directing.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Game development usually involves an overlap of these methods.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] For example, asset creation may be done via waterfall model, because requirements and specification are clear, but gameplay design might be done using iterative prototyping.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] There are many types of commonly used programming languages for game development as more suitable.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Java and Javascript are top choices due to animation capability.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Python also has many libraries that can produce suitable game development.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Minecraft for example is built entirely through Java.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] When programming the game the developers can either program the game animation using many graphical design libraries within the programming language.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Or if not they can load images direct into memory using the code to be the game animation.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Java has a high functionality for loading images into memory.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The late stage of pre-production may also be referred to as *proof of concept*, or *technical review* when more detailed game documents are produced.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Publishers have started to expect broader game proposals even featuring playable prototypes.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A *pitch*, *concept document*, proposal document, or *game proposal* is a short summary document intended to present the game's selling points and detail why the game would be profitable to develop.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Verbal pitches may be made to management within the developer company, and then presented to publishers.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A written document may need to be shown to publishers before funding is approved.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A game proposal may undergo one to several *green-light meetings* with publisher executives who determine if the game is to be developed.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The presentation of the project is often given by the game designers.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Demos may be created for the pitch; however may be unnecessary for established developers with good track records.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] If the developer acts as its own publisher, or both companies are subsidiaries of a single company, then only the upper management needs to give approval.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Before an approved design is completed, a skeleton crew of programmers and artists usually begins work.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Programmers may develop quick-and-dirty prototypes showcasing one or more features that stakeholders would like to see incorporated in the final product.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Artists may develop concept art and asset sketches as a springboard for developing real game assets.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Producers may work part-time on the game at this point, scaling up for full-time commitment as development progresses.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Game producer's work during pre-production is related to planning the schedule, budget and estimating tasks with the team.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The producer aims to create a solid production plan so that no delays are experienced at the start of the production.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Before a full-scale production can begin, the development team produces the first version of a game design document incorporating all or most of the material from the initial pitch.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The design document describes the game's concept and major gameplay elements in detail.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] It may also include preliminary sketches of various aspects of the game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The design document is sometimes accompanied by functional prototypes of some sections of the game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The design document remains a living document throughout the development—often changed weekly or even daily.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Compiling a list of game's needs is called "requirement capture".
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Writing prototypes of gameplay ideas and features is an important activity that allows programmers and game designers to experiment with different algorithms and usability scenarios for a game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A great deal of prototyping may take place during pre-production before the design document is complete and may, in fact, help determine what features the design specifies.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Prototyping at this stage is often done manually, (paper prototyping), not digitally, as this is often easier and faster to test and make changes before wasting time and resources on what could be a canceled idea or project.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Prototyping may also take place during active development to test new ideas as the game emerges.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Prototypes are often meant only to act as a proof of concept or to test ideas, by adding, modifying or removing some of the features.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Most algorithms and features debuted in a prototype may be ported to the game once they have been completed.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Often prototypes need to be developed quickly with very little time for up-front design (around 20 to 25§ minutes of testing).
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Therefore, usually very prolific programmers are called upon to quickly code these testbed tools.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] RAD tools may be used to aid in the quick development of these programs.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In case the prototype is in a physical form, programmers and designers alike will make the game with paper, dice, and other easy-to-access tools in order to make the prototype faster.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A successful development model is iterative prototyping, where design is refined based on current progress.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Production is the main stage of development when assets and source code for the game are produced.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Mainstream production is usually defined as the period of time when the project is fully staffed.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Programmers write new source code, artists develop game assets, such as, sprites or 3D models.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Sound engineers develop sound effects and composers develop music for the game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Level designers create levels, and writers write dialogue for cutscenes and NPCs.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Game designers continue to develop the game's design throughout production.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Game design is an essential and collaborative process of designing the content and rules of a game, requiring artistic and technical competence as well as writing skills.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Creativity and an open mind are vital for the completion of a successful video game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] During development, the game designer implements and modifies the game design to reflect the current vision of the game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Features and levels are often removed or added.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The art treatment may evolve and the backstory may change.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A new platform may be targeted as well as a new demographic.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] All these changes need to be documented and disseminated to the rest of the team.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Most changes occur as updates to the design document.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The programming of the game is handled by one or more game programmers.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] They develop prototypes to test ideas, many of which may never make it into the final game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The programmers incorporate new features demanded by the game design and fix any bugs introduced during the development process.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Even if an off-the-shelf game engine is used, a great deal of programming is required to customize almost every game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] From a time standpoint, the game's first level takes the longest to develop.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] As level designers and artists use the tools for level building, they request features and changes to the in-house tools that allow for quicker and higher-quality development.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Newly introduced features may cause old levels to become obsolete, so the levels developed early on may be repeatedly developed and discarded.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Because of the dynamic environment of game development, the design of early levels may also change over time.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] It is not uncommon to spend upwards of twelve months on one level of a game developed over the course of three years.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Later levels can be developed much more quickly as the feature set is more complete and the game vision is clearer and more stable.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] During development, artists make art assets according to specifications given by the designers.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Early in production, concept artists make concept art to guide the artistic direction of the game, rough art is made for prototypes, and the designers work with artists to design the visual style and visual language of the game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] As production goes on, more final art is made, and existing art is edited based on player feedback.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Game audio may be separated into three categories—sound effects, music, and voice-over.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Sound effect production is the production of sounds by either tweaking a sample to a desired effect or replicating it with real objects.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Sound effects include UI sound design, which effectively conveys information both for visible UI elements and as an auditory display.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] It provides sonic feedback for in-game interfaces, as well as contributing to the overall game aesthetic.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Sound effects are important and impact the game's delivery.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Music may be synthesized or performed live.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] There are four main ways in which music is presented in a game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A game title with 20 hours of single-player gameplay may feature around 1 hour.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Quality assurance of a video game product plays a significant role throughout the development cycle of a game, though comes more significantly into play as the game nears completion.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Because game development is focused on the presentation and gameplay as seen by the player, there often is little rigor in maintaining and testing backend code in the early stages of development since such code may be readily disregarded if there are changes found in gameplay.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Some automated testing may be used to ensure the core game engine operates as expected, but most game testing comes via game tester, who enter the testing process once a playable prototype is available.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] This may be one level or subset of the game software that can be used to any reasonable extent.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The use of testers may be lightweight at the early stages of development, but the testers' role becomes more predominant as the game nears completion, becoming a full-time role alongside development.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Early testing is considered a key part of game design; the most common issue raised in several published post-mortems on game development was the failure to start the testing process early.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] As code matures and the gameplay features solidify, then development typically includes more rigorous test controls such as regression testing to make sure new updates to the code base do not change working parts of the game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Games are complex software systems, and changes in one code area may unexpected cause a seemingly unrelated part of the game to fail.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Testers are tasked to repeatedly play through updated versions of games in these later stages to look for any issues or bugs not otherwise found from automated testing.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Because this can be a monotonous task of playing the same game over and over, this process can lead to games frequently being released with uncaught bugs or glitches.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] There are other factors simply inherent to video games that can make testing difficult.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Despite the dangers of overlooking regression testing, some game developers and publishers fail to test the full feature suite of the game and ship a game with bugs.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] This can result in customer dissatisfaction and failure to meet sales goals.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] When this does happen, most developers and publishers quickly release patches that fix the bugs and make the game fully playable again.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Certain publishing models are designed specifically to accommodate the fact that first releases of games may be bug-ridden but will be fixed post-release.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The early access model invites players to pay into a game before its planned release and helps to provide feedback and bug reports.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Mobile games and games with live services are also anticipated to be updated on a frequent basis, offset by pre-release testing with live feedback and bug reports.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Commercial game development projects may be required to meet milestones set by the publisher.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Milestones mark major events during game development and are used to track game's progress.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Such milestones may be, for example, *first playable*, *alpha*, or *beta* game versions.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Project milestones depend on the developer schedules.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Milestones are usually based on multiple short descriptions for functionality; examples may be "Player roaming around in-game environment" or "Physics working, collisions, vehicle" etc.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] These milestones are usually how the developer gets paid; sometimes as "an advance against royalty".
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] These milestones are listed, anywhere from three to twenty depending on the developer and publisher.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The milestone list is usually a collaborative agreement between the publisher and developer.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The developer usually advocates for making the milestone descriptions as simple as possible; depending on the specific publisher - the milestone agreements may get very detailed for a specific game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] When working with a good publisher, the "spirit of the law" is usually adhered to regarding milestone completion... in other words, if the milestone is 90% complete the milestone is usually paid with the understanding that it will be 100% complete by the next due milestone.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] It is a collaborative agreement between publisher and developer, and usually (but not always) the developer is constrained by heavy monthly development expenses that need to be met.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Also, sometimes milestones are "swapped", the developer or publisher may mutually agree to amend the agreement and rearrange milestone goals depending on changing requirements and development resources available.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Milestone agreements are usually included as part of the legal development contracts.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] After each "milestone" there is usually a payment arrangement.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Some very established developers may simply have a milestone agreement based on the amount of time the game is in development (monthly/quarterly) and not specific game functionality - this is not as common as detailed functionality "milestone lists".
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] There is no industry standard for defining milestones, and such varies depending on publisher, year, or project.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The *first playable* is the game version containing representative gameplay and assets, this is the first version with functional major gameplay elements.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] It is often based on the prototype created in pre-production.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Alpha and first playable are sometimes used to refer to a single milestone, however, large projects require first playable before feature complete alpha.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] First playable occurs 12 to 18 months before code release.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] It is sometimes referred to as the "Pre-Alpha" stage.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In most AAA game development, games are announced a year or more in advance and given a planned release date or approximate window so that they can promote and market the game, establish orders with retailers, and entice consumers to pre-order the game.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Delaying the release of a video game can have a negative financial impact on publishers and developers, and extensive delays may lead to project cancellation and employee layoffs.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] To ensure a game makes a set release date, publishers and developers may require their employees to work overtime to complete the game, which is considered common in the industry.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] This overtime is often referred to as "crunch time" or "crunch mode".
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In 2004 and afterwards, the culture of crunch time in the industry came under scrutiny, leading many publishers and developers to reduce the expectation on developers for overtime work and better schedule management, though crunch time still can occur.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] After the game goes gold and ships, some developers will give team members *comp time* (perhaps up to a week or two) to compensate for the overtime put in to complete the game, though this compensation is not standard.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Once a game ships, the maintenance phase for the video game begins.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Games developed for video game consoles have had almost no maintenance period in the past.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The shipped game would forever house as many bugs and features as when released.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] This was common for consoles since all consoles had identical or nearly identical hardware; making incompatibility, the cause of many bugs, a non-issue.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In this case, maintenance would only occur in the case of a port, sequel, or enhanced remake that reuses a large portion of the engine and assets.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In recent times popularity of online console games has grown, and online capable video game consoles and online services such as Xbox Live for the Xbox have developed.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Developers can maintain their software through downloadable patches.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] These changes would not have been possible in the past without the widespread availability of the Internet.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Game developers try to account for the majority of configurations and hardware.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] However, the number of possible configurations of hardware and software inevitably leads to the discovery of game-breaking circumstances that the programmers and testers did not account for.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Programmers wait for a period to get as many bug reports as possible.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Once the developer thinks they've obtained enough feedback, the programmers start working on a patch.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The patch may take weeks or months to develop, but it is intended to fix most accounted bugs and problems with the game that were overlooked in past code releases, or in rare cases, fix unintended problems caused by previous patches.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Occasionally a patch may include extra features or content or may even alter gameplay.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In the case of a massively multiplayer online game (MMOG), such as a MMORPG or MMORTS, the shipment of the game is the starting phase of maintenance.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The maintenance staff for such an online game can number in the dozens, sometimes including members of the original programming team, as the game world is continuously changed and iterated and new features are added.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Some developers implement a public test realm or player test realm (PTR) in order to test out significant upcoming changes prior to release.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] These specialized servers offer similar benefits as beta testing, where players get to preview new features while the developer gathers data about bugs and game balance.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Several development disciplines, such as audio, dialogue, or motion capture, occur for relatively short periods of time.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Efficient employment of these roles requires either a large development house with multiple simultaneous title productions or outsourcing from third-party vendors.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Employing personnel for these tasks full-time is expensive, so a majority of developers outsource a portion of the work.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Outsourcing plans are conceived during the pre-production stage; where the time and finances required for outsourced work are estimated.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Outsourced work is sometimes anonymous, i.e. not credited on the final product.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] This might go against the wishes of the developer, or it is something they reluctantly consent to because it is the only work they can get.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] See Video game controversies § Lack of crediting for more information on this.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] However, anonymity can also be agreed upon, or even desired by the outsourced party.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A 2015 *Polygon* article stated that this practice is known as **ghost development**.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Ghost developers are hired by other developers to provide assistance, by publishers to develop a title they designed, or by companies outside the gaming industry.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] These businesses prefer to keep this hidden from the public to protect their brand equity, not wanting consumers or investors to know that they rely on external help.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Ghost development can involve (small) portions of a project, but there have been instances of entire games being outsourced without the studio being credited.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Ghost development has a particularly long history in the Japanese video game industry.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Probably the best-known example is Tose.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Founded in 1979, this 'behind-the-scenes' agent has either developed or helped develop over 2,000 games as of 2017, most of them anonymously.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] This includes uncredited contributions to multiple *Resident Evil*, *Metal Gear*, and *Dragon Quest* titles.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Another example is Tokyo-based Hyde, which worked on *Final Fantasy*, *Persona*, and *Yakuza* games.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Its president, Kenichi Yanagihara, stated that the approach stems from Japanese culture, in which many people prefer not to seek the limelight.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The game production has similar distribution methods to those of music and film industries.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The publisher's marketing team targets the game for a specific market and then advertises it.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The team advises the developer on target demographics and market trends, as well as suggests specific features.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The game is then advertised and the game's high concept is incorporated into the promotional material, ranging from magazine ads to TV spots.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Communication between developer and marketing is important.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The length and purpose of a game demo depends on the purpose of the demo and target audience.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A game's demo may range between a few seconds (such as clips or screenshots) to hours of gameplay.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The demo is usually intended for journalists, buyers, trade shows, general public, or internal employees (who, for example, may need to familiarize with the game to promote it).
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Demos are produced with public relations, marketing and sales in mind, maximizing the presentation effectiveness.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] As a game nears completion, the publisher will want to showcase a demo of the title at trade shows.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Many games have a "Trade Show demo" scheduled.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The major annual trade shows are, for example, Electronic Entertainment Expo (E3) or Penny Arcade Expo (PAX).
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] E3 is the largest show in North America.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] E3 is hosted primarily for marketing and business deals.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] New games and platforms are announced at E3 and it received broad press coverage.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Thousands of products are on display and press demonstration schedules are kept.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In the 2000s E3 became a more closed-door event and many advertisers have withdrawn, reducing E3's budget.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] PAX, created by authors of Penny Arcade blog and web-comic, is a mature and playful event with a player-centred philosophy.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] A game created in one language may also be published in other countries which speak a different language.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] For that region, the developers may want to translate the game to make it more accessible.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] For example, some games created for PlayStation Vita were initially published in Japanese language, like *Soul Sacrifice*.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Non-native speakers of the game's original language may have to wait for the translation of the game to their language.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] But most modern big-budget games take localization into account during the development process and the games are released in several different languages simultaneously.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Localization is the process of translating the language assets in a game into other languages.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] By localizing games, they increase their level of accessibility where games could help to expend the international markets effectively.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Game localization is generally known as language translations yet a "full localization" of a game is a complex project.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] There are various essential elements in localizing a game including translating the language of the game to adjusting in-game assets for different cultures to reach more potential consumers in other geographies (or globalization for short).
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The translation seems to fall into the scope of localization, which itself constitutes a substantially broader endeavour.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] These include the different levels of translation to the globalization of the game itself.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] However, certain developers seem to be divided on whether globalization falls under localization or not.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Moreover, to fit into the local markets, game production companies often change or redesign the graphic designs or the packaging of the game for marketing purposes.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] For example, the popular game *Assassin's Creed* has two different packaging designs for the European and US markets.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] By localizing the graphics and packaging designs, companies might arouse better connections and attention from the consumers from various regions.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The costs of developing a video game varies widely depending on several factors including team size, game genre and scope, and other factors such as intellectual property licensing costs.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Most video game consoles also require development licensing costs which include game development kits for building and testing software.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Game budgets also typically include costs for marketing and promotion, which can be on the same order in cost as the development budget.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Prior to the 1990s, game development budgets, when reported, typically were on the average of US$1–5 million, with known outliers, such as the $20–25 million that Atari had paid to license the rights for *E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial* in addition to development costs.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Koster reported average budgets were around $100 million by 2017, and could reach over $200 million by the early 2020s.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Koster asserts these trends are partially tied to the technological Moore's law that gave more computational power for developers to work into their games, but also related to expectations for content from players in newer games and the number of players games are expected to draw.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Shawn Layden, former CEO of Sony Interactive Entertainment, affirmed that the costs for each generation of PlayStation consoles nearly doubled, with PlayStation 4 games have average budgets of $100 million and anticipating that PlayStation 5 games could reach $200 million.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The rising costs of budgets of AAA games in the early 2000s led publishers to become risk-averse, staying to titles that were most likely to be high-selling games to recoup their costs.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] As a result of this risk aversion, the selection of AAA games in the mid-2000s became rather similar, and gave the opportunity for indie games that provided more experimental and unique gameplay concepts to expand around that time.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Costs of development for AAA games continued to rise over the next two decades; a report by the United Kingdom's Competition and Markets Authority regarding the proposed acquisition of Activision Blizzard by Microsoft in 2023.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Costs slowing increased from 1–4 million in 2000, to over $5 million in 2006, then to over $20 million by 2010, followed by $50 million to $150 million by 2018, and $200 million and up by 2023.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In some cases, several AAA games exceeded $1 billion to make, split between $500-$600M to develop and a similar amount for marketing.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In court documents from regulatory review of the Activision Blizzard merger, reviewed by *The Verge*, the costs of Sony's first party games like *Horizon Forbidden West* and *The Last of Us Part II* had exceeded $200 million.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Independent games or *indie games* are produced by individuals and small teams with no large-scale developer or publisher affiliations.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Indie developers generally rely on Internet distribution schemes.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Many hobbyist indie developers create mods of existing games.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Indie developers are credited for creative game ideas (for example, *Darwinia*, *Weird Worlds*, *World of Goo*).
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Current economic viability of indie development is questionable, however in recent years internet delivery platforms, such as, Xbox Live Arcade and Steam have improved indie game success.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In fact, some indie games have become very successful, such as *Braid*, *World of Goo*, and *Minecraft*.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In recent years many communities have emerged in support of indie games such as the popular indie game marketplace Itch.io, indie game YouTube channels and a large indie community on Steam.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] It is common for indie game developers to release games for free and generate revenue through other means such as microtransactions (in-game transactions), in-game advertisements and crowd-funding services like Patreon and Kickstarter.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The video game industry (formally referred to as interactive entertainment) is the economic sector involved with the development, marketing and sale of video games.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] The industry sports several unique approaches.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In the United States, in the early history of video game development, the prominent locale for game development was the corridor from San Francisco to Silicon Valley in California.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Most new developers in the US open near such "hot beds".
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] At present, many large publishers still operate there, such as: Activision Blizzard, Capcom Entertainment, Crystal Dynamics, Electronic Arts, Namco Bandai Games, Sega of America, and Sony Computer Entertainment America.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Many universities and design schools are offering classes specifically focused on game development.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Some have built strategic alliances with major game development companies.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] These alliances ensure that students have access to the latest technologies and are provided the opportunity to find jobs within the gaming industry once qualified.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Many innovative ideas are presented at conferences, such as Independent Games Festival (IGF) or Game Developers Conference (GDC).
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Indie game development may motivate students who produce a game for their final projects or thesis and may open their own game company.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Video game industry employment is fairly volatile, similar to other artistic industries including television, music, etc.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Scores of game development studios crop up, work on one game, and then quickly go under.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] This may be one reason why game developers tend to congregate geographically; if their current studio goes under, developers can flock to an adjacent one or start another from the ground up.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] In an industry where only the top 20% of products make a profit, it is easy to understand this fluctuation.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Numerous games may start development and are cancelled, or perhaps even completed but never published.
[src:odin-lang/video-game-development-p02] Experienced game developers may work for years and yet never ship a title: such is the nature of the business.
